\begin_layout Section
Precautionary motive and cash holdings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Increase in cash holding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bates2009whydo"

\end_inset

 find that the US firms hold more and more cash over time.
 This increase in cash could be explained by two motives: 
\emph on
agency problem
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
precautionary motive
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, firms tend to increase cash because they are less likely to pay dividends
 in an influential paper of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fama2001disappearing"

\end_inset

.
 This evidence seems to consistent with the agency theory.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jensen1986agencycost"

\end_inset

 argue that entrenched CEOs tend to hold more cash instead of paying out
 to shareholders when they have poor investment opportunities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, this increase in cash is also consistent with some change in firm
 characteristics such as: firms' cash flows are more volatile, firms hold
 less inventories and account receivables, and they invest more in R&D relative
 to capital expenditure over time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To distinguish between these two views, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bates2009whydo"

\end_inset

 adopt two smart tests:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
First, they consider the increase in cash of firms in the top highest G-index
 quintile and the lowest G-index quintile.
 The agency predicts that firms in high G-index quintile should increase
 cash more but the empirical result contradicts to this prediction.
 In particular, all G-index quintile see the increase in cash holdings,
 but the increase in more pronounced among firms in the lowest G-index quintile.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Second, if the agency motive is true, we should see the increase in cash
 holding is negatively associated with firm value.
 Again, the empirical result is contrast to the prediction.
 Increase in cash holding indeed has positive impact on firm value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Cash increase and refinancing risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "harford2014refinancing"

\end_inset

 propose another reason to explain why firms hold more cash: to prevent
 refinancing risk for short debt maturity.
 If lenders give a firm a short maturity loan, firms need to hold more cash
 to mitigate the refinancing concern.
 Applying the cash-cash flows sensitivity of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "almeida2004thecash"

\end_inset

 that financial constrained firms save more cash from cash flows for future
 investment, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "harford2014refinancing"

\end_inset

 show that firms in the top quintile of long-run debt due in 3 years save
 well over 5 cents per dollar of cash flows in comparison to only 3.4 cents
 per dollar of cash flows for an average firm.
 They also find a shorted debt maturity for the US firms over time, which
 is consistent with the time series of cash holdings in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bates2009whydo"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With respect to value of cash holding and refinancing risk, following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "faulkender2006corporate"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "harford2014refinancing"

\end_inset

 regress firm value on change in cash reserve, refinancing risk, and their
 interaction.
 They find that the estimated coefficient of the interaction is positive,
 so higher cash helps to mitigate the risk of refinancing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This evidence could relate to our work in managerial ability and bank loans.
 We could not find significant positive relation between loan maturity and
 managerial ability.
 In our working paper, we also find that firms with high-ability CEOs seem
 to have less financial constraints.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Agency evidence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, we still find some supporting evidence for the long-lived agency
 motive.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "harford2008corporate"

\end_inset

 use high G-index and low insider ownership as measure for weak governance.
 They attempt to link governance and investment and payout decisions.
 Weak governance firms tend to hold less cash because they spend most of
 cash on M&A and expenditure.
 The interaction between governance and cash reserve suggests that the 
\emph on
spending effect
\emph default
 is stronger with the presence of excess cash.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With respect to payout decisions, firms with weak governance tend to repurchase
 rather than cash dividend.
 They also have no commitment to maintain future dividend stream.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Conflict of agency and cash holdings (or public vs.
 private firms' cash holding)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Weak-governed firms tend to overinvest.
 Among public firms, weak-governed firms tend to spend excess cash in other
 asset forms (e.g., in M&A) and well-governed firms tend to payout or reduce
 leverage.
 However, the speed of spending of weak-governed firms are faster than the
 speed of payout and relax leverage of well-governed firms.
 Thus, weak-governed firms also set a high target level of cash to have
 more freedom from external monitoring.
 As a results, higher agency conflicts lead to a higher cash holdings of
 public firms compared to private firms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gao2013determinants"

\end_inset

.
 Some important findings of this paper is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Despite financing frictions (less access to external finance) and higher
 precautionary motive, private firms hold about half as much cash as public
 firms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The driver of this finding is because public firms have higher agency problems.
 Thus, public first set a higher targe cash level than the private firms.
 This is because entrenched managers, who prefer more internal financial
 slack, appear to set higher target cash level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

