\begin_layout Section
Diversification and cash holdings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Professor Duchin has a bunch of work relating to diversification.
 Some of them relate to the cash holdings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "duchin2010cashholdings"

\end_inset

 propose the relation between cross-divisional correlation of investment
 opportunities and financing deficit/gap (Q-CF correlation) and cash flows
 could affect the diversified firms' cash holdings.
 If cross-divisional Q and CF correlation are lower, these firms are well-divers
ified and have coinsurance effect so they have less incentive to hold cash
 fow precautionary motive.
 If Q-CF correlation is higher, firms have less financing gap, so the hold
 less cash.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This finding could be explained by the governance and cross-divisional transfer.
 In good governance and in firms with high transfer, firms hold less cash.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "duchin2013divisional"

\end_inset

 provide evidence that CEO allocate more capital to divisional managers
 with high social connection to him.
 This finding could be explained by two hypotheses: (i) favoritism hypothesis
 and (ii) information hypothesis.
 These two hypotheses have contrasting predictions to firm value: favoritism
 predicts negative value and information predicts a positive effect.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In well-governed and high information asymmetric firms, divisional managers
 tend to give more valuable information/advice to CEOs, social connection
 between them gives more efficient investment and higher firm value.
 In contrast, at firms with poor governance, the social connection between
 them negatively affects investment efficiency and firm value.
 This paper, thus, clearly show the both bright side and dark side of diversific
ation.
\end_layout

